Document: Exporting for Linux  
Path: godot/tutorials/export/exporting_for_linux.rst  
Summary: This guide explains how to export a Godot project for Linux distribution using the export system.  

The simplest way to distribute a game for PC is to copy the executable (godot), compress the folder and send it to someone else. However, this is often not desired. Godot offers a more elegant approach for PC distribution when using the export system. When exporting for Linux, the exporter takes all the project files and creates a data.pck file. This file is bundled with a specially optimized binary that is smaller, faster and does not contain the editor and debugger. If you're looking to compile editor or export template binaries from source instead, read doc_compiling_for_linuxbsd.
---CHUNK---
Document: Exporting for Linux
Path: godot/tutorials/export/exporting_for_linux.rst
Summary: Overview of supported Linux processor architectures for Godot exports and recommendations for each

There are 7 different processor architectures that exported Godot projects can run on in Linux: x86_64, x86_32, arm64, arm32, rv64, ppc64, loongarch64. The default is x86_64, which is the most common architecture of PC processors today. All modern Intel and AMD processors as of writing this are x86_64.

x86_32 will produce 32bit executables that can run on 32bit only distributions of Linux as well as some modern 64bit distributions. Note: This option is not recommended unless targeting old 32bit distributions. Warning: Several prominent distributions, such as Fedora, have been discussing removing their 32bit libraries which would prevent executables made this way from running on future versions.

arm64 executables run on 64bit ARM processors. Raspberry Pi 3 and newer use 64bit ARM processors. If uploading to platforms supporting multiple executables like itch.io, and targeting devices like Pi 5, this version is recommended.

arm32 executables are for older 32bit ARM processors used in Raspberry Pi 1 and 2. Not recommended unless targeting specific legacy hardware.

rv64 is for RISC-V processors, ppc64 for 64bit PowerPC processors, and loongarch64 for 64bit LoongArch processors. These are niche architectures primarily used by enthusiasts. Export templates for these are not provided by Godot. Instructions for compiling the engine for RISC-V and creating custom export templates can be found on the doc_compiling_for_linuxbsd page.
---CHUNK---
Document: Exporting for Linux
Path: godot/tutorials/export/exporting_for_linux.rst
Summary: How to use environment variables to override Linux export settings during the export process.

Environment variables can be used to set export options outside of the editor. These variables override values set in the export menu during the export process. The following environment variables are available for Linux exports:

- Encryption / Encryption Key: GODOT_SCRIPT_ENCRYPTION_KEY
